solution:
This is a finite geometric series with first term $\frac{1}{3}$, common ratio $\frac{1}{3}$ and $6$ terms. Therefore the sum is: $$\frac{\frac{1}{3}\left(1-\frac{1}{3^{6}}\right)}{1-\frac{1}{3}}
=\frac{\frac{3^{6}-1}{3^{7}}}{\frac{2}{3}}
= \frac{3^{6}-1}{2\cdot3^{6}}=\frac{729-1}{2\cdot 729} = \boxed{\frac{364}{729}}.$$

We apply the distributive property repeatedly:

\begin{align*}
(x+10)(2y+10) &= x(2y+10) + 10(2y+10)\\
&= x\cdot 2y + x\cdot 10 + 10\cdot 2y + 10\cdot 10\\
&= \boxed{2xy + 10x + 20y + 100}.
\end{align*}

The greatest common factor of $37a^2$ and $111a$ is $37a$. We factor $37a$ out of both terms to get\begin{align*}
37a^2 + 111a &= 37a \cdot a+ 37a \cdot 3\\
&=\boxed{37a(a+3)}
\end{align*}

